/* ============================================================================
   linux+ :: content/domain2.js
   Lazy-loaded textbook reading module for XK0-006 Domain 2 (Services and User Management).
   Populates LINUXPLUS.reading[2]. Loaded on demand by app.js.
   ============================================================================ */
window.LINUXPLUS = window.LINUXPLUS || {}; LINUXPLUS.reading = LINUXPLUS.reading || {};
LINUXPLUS.reading[2] = [];
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Navigating and Managing Files and Directories", body:"<p>Every administrative task eventually comes down to moving through the filesystem tree and manipulating the files in it. Mastery of a small set of commands -- and of how Linux interprets paths -- is the difference between confident, fast work and tentative guessing at a production prompt.</p><h3>Orienting Yourself: pwd, cd, and ls</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>current working directory</span> is the directory your shell is presently sitting in, and <code>pwd</code> (print working directory) prints its absolute path. You move with <code>cd</code> (change directory): <code>cd /var/log</code> jumps to an absolute location, <code>cd ..</code> goes up one level, <code>cd ~</code> or a bare <code>cd</code> returns to your home directory, and <code>cd -</code> toggles back to the previous directory. The workhorse for listing is <code>ls</code>. By itself it lists names, but its flags are where the value lies. <code>ls -l</code> gives the long format with permissions, link count, owner, group, size, and modification time; <code>ls -a</code> reveals hidden dotfiles such as <code>.bashrc</code>; and <code>ls -i</code> prepends each file's <span class='keyterm'>inode</span> number. These combine, so <code>ls -lai</code> is a common one-liner. A typical long line reads <code>-rw-r--r-- 1 jane staff 2048 Jun 29 09:14 report.txt</code>: type and mode, link count, owner, group, byte size, mtime, and name.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>ls -l</code></td><td>Long listing: perms, owner, size, mtime</td></tr><tr><td><code>ls -a</code></td><td>Include hidden (dot) files</td></tr><tr><td><code>ls -i</code></td><td>Show inode numbers</td></tr><tr><td><code>ls -lh</code></td><td>Human-readable sizes (K, M, G)</td></tr><tr><td><code>ls -lt</code></td><td>Sort newest first by mtime</td></tr><tr><td><code>ls -lS</code></td><td>Sort largest first by size</td></tr><tr><td><code>ls -lR</code></td><td>Recurse into subdirectories</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Absolute versus Relative Paths</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>absolute path</span> begins with <code>/</code> and is unambiguous from anywhere on the system, for example <code>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</code>. A <span class='keyterm'>relative path</span> is resolved from your current directory, so from <code>/etc/ssh</code> the file is simply <code>sshd_config</code> and the parent's neighbor is <code>../hosts</code>. The shortcuts <code>.</code> (here), <code>..</code> (up one), and <code>~</code> (home) are interpreted by the shell. Scripts should prefer absolute paths so they behave the same no matter where they are invoked. A common gotcha: <code>cd ~bob</code> means bob's home directory, not a subdirectory named <code>~bob</code>, because the shell expands the tilde-plus-name form to the named user's home from <code>/etc/passwd</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Notation</th><th>Resolves to</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/etc/hosts</code></td><td>Absolute, from filesystem root</td></tr><tr><td><code>./run.sh</code></td><td>File in the current directory</td></tr><tr><td><code>../config</code></td><td>Sibling via the parent directory</td></tr><tr><td><code>~/notes</code></td><td>notes under your home directory</td></tr><tr><td><code>~bob/data</code></td><td>data under bob's home directory</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Creating, Copying, Moving, and Removing</h3><p>To create things: <code>mkdir reports</code> makes a directory, <code>mkdir -p a/b/c</code> builds a whole nested chain in one step, and <code>touch notes.txt</code> creates an empty file (or updates an existing file's timestamps). To copy, <code>cp src dst</code> duplicates a file; <code>cp -r</code> recurses into directories, <code>cp -p</code> preserves ownership and timestamps, <code>cp -a</code> archives (recursive plus preserve plus follow no symlinks), and <code>cp -i</code> prompts before overwriting. The <code>mv</code> command both moves and renames -- <code>mv old.txt new.txt</code> renames, <code>mv file.txt /backup/</code> relocates. Removal is unforgiving: <code>rm file</code> deletes a file, <code>rm -r dir</code> deletes a directory tree, and <code>rm -f</code> forces past prompts. There is no recycle bin, so <code>rm -rf /</code> or a stray space in <code>rm -rf / home/old</code> is catastrophic. Empty directories can be removed safely with <code>rmdir</code>, which refuses to delete a non-empty directory and so acts as a guard rail.</p><h3>Inspecting Files: file and stat</h3><p>Two commands report on a file without opening it. <code>file report.dat</code> examines the content (magic bytes) and tells you whether it is ASCII text, a PNG image, an ELF executable, or gzip data -- never trust the extension alone. <code>stat report.dat</code> dumps the inode metadata: exact byte size, block count, permissions in both symbolic and octal form, owner and group IDs, and the three timestamps. Linux tracks <span class='keyterm'>atime</span> (last access), <span class='keyterm'>mtime</span> (last content change), and <span class='keyterm'>ctime</span> (last inode change, such as a permission edit); note there is no true creation time on traditional filesystems. <code>stat</code> is the authoritative source when you need precise timestamps or the inode number behind a name, and <code>stat -c '%a %n' file</code> prints just the octal mode and name for scripting.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Remember that <code>mkdir -p</code> creates intermediate directories and never errors if the path already exists, which makes it safe inside scripts. Conversely <code>rmdir</code> only removes empty directories -- to delete a directory with contents you need <code>rm -r</code>. And know the timestamp trio: atime (access), mtime (modify content), ctime (change inode metadata).</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Finding Files: find, locate, which, and Comparison Tools", body:"<p>On a server with hundreds of thousands of files you cannot browse to what you need; you search for it. Linux offers a real-time recursive search, a fast index-backed lookup, a command-resolver, and tools to compare files line by line.</p><h3>find: the Real-Time Search Engine</h3><p>The <code>find</code> command walks a directory tree live and tests each entry against expressions. The syntax is <code>find STARTPATH TESTS ACTIONS</code>. Common tests include <code>-name</code> (glob on the filename, case-sensitive; <code>-iname</code> is the insensitive form), <code>-type</code> (<code>f</code> for regular file, <code>d</code> for directory, <code>l</code> for symlink), <code>-size</code> (<code>+100M</code> means larger than 100 megabytes), <code>-perm</code> (match a permission mode), and <code>-mtime</code> (modification age in days; <code>-mtime -7</code> is changed within the last week, <code>+30</code> is older than 30 days). The killer feature is <code>-exec</code>, which runs a command on each match, terminated by <code>\\;</code> with <code>{}</code> standing in for the path. For large result sets, <code>-exec cmd {} +</code> batches many paths into one invocation, far faster than one process per file.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Expression</th><th>Matches / does</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>find /var -name '*.log'</code></td><td>Files ending in .log under /var</td></tr><tr><td><code>find . -type d -name cache</code></td><td>Directories named cache</td></tr><tr><td><code>find / -size +500M</code></td><td>Files larger than 500 MB</td></tr><tr><td><code>find /tmp -mtime +30</code></td><td>Files older than 30 days</td></tr><tr><td><code>find . -name '*.tmp' -delete</code></td><td>Delete each matching file</td></tr><tr><td><code>find /home -user bob</code></td><td>Files owned by user bob</td></tr><tr><td><code>find / -perm -4000</code></td><td>Find setuid binaries</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>locate: the Index Lookup</h3><p>Where <code>find</code> reads the disk every time, <span class='keyterm'>locate</span> queries a pre-built database and returns results almost instantly. The trade-off is freshness: the database is rebuilt periodically (usually by a daily cron job or systemd timer) with <code>updatedb</code>, so a file created minutes ago may not appear until the next index run. Run <code>sudo updatedb</code> to refresh it manually. Use <code>locate</code> when you want speed and the file is not brand-new; use <code>find</code> when you need current results or rich tests. The modern implementation is usually <code>mlocate</code> or <code>plocate</code>, which check permissions so users only see files they could reach.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Speed</th><th>Freshness</th><th>Rich tests</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>find</code></td><td>Slow (walks disk)</td><td>Always current</td><td>Yes (size, time, perm)</td></tr><tr><td><code>locate</code></td><td>Instant (index)</td><td>As old as last updatedb</td><td>Name only</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>which, type, and the Command Path</h3><p>The <code>which</code> command answers a narrower question: given a command name, which executable in your <code>$PATH</code> will actually run? <code>which python3</code> might return <code>/usr/bin/python3</code>. It only searches the directories in <code>PATH</code>, so it is the right tool when two versions of a program are installed and you need to know which one wins. The related <code>type</code> built-in also reveals shell aliases and functions that <code>which</code> cannot see -- <code>type ll</code> may report it is an alias for <code>ls -l</code> -- and <code>command -v</code> is the portable POSIX equivalent used in scripts.</p><h3>Comparing Files: diff and sdiff</h3><p>To see how two files differ, <code>diff old.conf new.conf</code> prints the changed lines in a compact format; <code>diff -u</code> produces the unified format used by patches, with context lines and <code>+</code>/<code>-</code> markers. <code>sdiff</code> shows the two files side by side in two columns with a gutter marking differences (<code>|</code> changed, <code>&lt;</code> only in left, <code>&gt;</code> only in right), which many people find easier to read for configuration review. Both are invaluable when validating that a deployed config matches a known-good template, and <code>diff -r dir1 dir2</code> compares whole trees recursively.</p><p>A few practical habits make searching reliable. Always quote glob patterns passed to <code>find</code> -- writing <code>find . -name *.log</code> unquoted lets the shell expand the asterisk before find ever sees it, producing surprising errors, so write <code>find . -name '*.log'</code> instead. When a search must not descend into mounted filesystems, add <code>-xdev</code> to keep find on a single device, which is essential when scanning <code>/</code> on a box with network mounts. To suppress the permission-denied noise that appears when searching system-wide as a normal user, redirect standard error with <code>find / -name secret 2&gt;/dev/null</code>. And when you only need a count or the first few hits, piping into <code>head</code> or <code>wc -l</code> turns a sprawling result into something actionable. These small refinements separate a search that hangs on a busy server from one that returns exactly what you wanted in seconds.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A web app cannot find its data and you suspect a config drifted. You run <code>diff -u /etc/app/app.conf /backup/app.conf.good</code> and immediately see a single line where the database host changed. The unified diff hands you the exact edit to make. Had you wanted to locate every stray <code>.bak</code> file the deploy left behind, <code>find /etc/app -name '*.bak' -mtime -1</code> would surface only today's.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Links and Device Files", body:"<p>Not every entry in the filesystem is a plain file. Linux supports links that let one piece of data have several names, and special files that represent hardware and inter-process channels. Understanding the inode is the key that unlocks all of them.</p><h3>Inodes: the Real File</h3><p>On disk, a file's metadata and data-block pointers live in an <span class='keyterm'>inode</span>, a numbered structure. The name you see in a directory is merely a pointer to an inode; the directory entry maps a human name to an inode number. This indirection is what makes links possible. View a file's inode with <code>ls -i</code> or <code>stat</code>. A filesystem has a finite number of inodes fixed at creation, so a partition can report <span class='keyterm'>no space left on device</span> even with free bytes if it has exhausted its inodes -- check with <code>df -i</code>, which shows inode usage rather than block usage.</p><h3>Hard Links versus Symbolic Links</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>hard link</span> is a second directory entry pointing at the very same inode. Created with <code>ln target linkname</code>, both names are equal peers -- there is no original. The inode's link count (shown in <code>ls -l</code>) increments, and the data is only freed when that count reaches zero, so deleting one name leaves the other fully working. Because hard links share an inode, they cannot cross filesystems and cannot point to directories. A <span class='keyterm'>symbolic link</span> (symlink, or soft link), created with <code>ln -s target linkname</code>, is instead a tiny special file whose content is a path string pointing at the target. It can cross filesystems and link to directories, but if the target is deleted the symlink becomes a <span class='keyterm'>dangling link</span> that resolves to nothing.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Hard link</th><th>Symbolic link</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Created with</td><td><code>ln a b</code></td><td><code>ln -s a b</code></td></tr><tr><td>Points to</td><td>The inode</td><td>A pathname</td></tr><tr><td>Cross filesystem</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Link to directory</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Survives target deletion</td><td>Yes (shares data)</td><td>No (dangles)</td></tr><tr><td>Own inode</td><td>Same as target</td><td>Separate</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Block and Character Device Files</h3><p>The <code>/dev</code> directory is full of <span class='keyterm'>device files</span> that give programs a file-like interface to hardware. A <span class='keyterm'>block device</span> transfers data in fixed-size blocks and supports random access -- disks such as <code>/dev/sda</code> are block devices, marked with a <code>b</code> in the first column of <code>ls -l</code>. A <span class='keyterm'>character device</span> transfers data as a stream of bytes one at a time -- terminals (<code>/dev/tty</code>), serial ports, and <code>/dev/null</code> are character devices, marked with a <code>c</code>. Each device file carries a <span class='keyterm'>major number</span> identifying the driver and a <span class='keyterm'>minor number</span> identifying the specific device, both visible in <code>ls -l /dev</code> where a normal size column is replaced by the two numbers. The <code>mknod</code> command can create device nodes by hand, though <code>udev</code> populates <code>/dev</code> automatically at runtime.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Type char</th><th>File type</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>-</code></td><td>Regular file</td><td>report.txt</td></tr><tr><td><code>d</code></td><td>Directory</td><td>/etc</td></tr><tr><td><code>l</code></td><td>Symbolic link</td><td>/bin -&gt; /usr/bin</td></tr><tr><td><code>b</code></td><td>Block device</td><td>/dev/sda</td></tr><tr><td><code>c</code></td><td>Character device</td><td>/dev/null</td></tr><tr><td><code>p</code></td><td>Named pipe (FIFO)</td><td>mypipe</td></tr><tr><td><code>s</code></td><td>Socket</td><td>/run/docker.sock</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Named Pipes (FIFOs)</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>named pipe</span>, or FIFO (first-in, first-out), is a special file created with <code>mkfifo mypipe</code> that lets two unrelated processes communicate: one writes to the pipe, another reads from it, and the kernel buffers the stream in order. Unlike an anonymous shell pipe (<code>|</code>) that exists only for the life of a command, a named pipe persists on disk and appears in <code>ls -l</code> with a <code>p</code> type character. They are useful for connecting a producer and consumer that are started separately -- a write to the pipe blocks until something opens it for reading, which surprises the unwary.</p><p>Links solve real administrative problems. A symlink lets you present a stable path that points at a versioned target, so <code>/opt/app/current</code> can be a symlink swung from <code>release-1.4</code> to <code>release-1.5</code> with a single <code>ln -sfn</code> command, giving you an atomic, instantly reversible deployment. Hard links are the mechanism behind space-efficient snapshot backups: tools like <code>rsync --link-dest</code> create new backup trees where unchanged files are hard links to the previous run, so a hundred daily snapshots of a mostly-static directory consume the disk of roughly one. When you remove a symlink with <code>rm</code>, you delete only the link, not its target -- but beware that a trailing slash, as in <code>rm linkdir/</code>, may follow the link to the directory it points at. Use <code>ls -l</code> to confirm what an entry actually is before deleting, and <code>readlink -f</code> to resolve a chain of symlinks down to the final real path. The device-file abstraction is equally powerful: writing to <code>/dev/null</code> discards data, reading from <code>/dev/zero</code> yields endless zero bytes for initializing files, and <code>/dev/urandom</code> supplies cryptographic-quality randomness, all through the same open-read-write interface as an ordinary file.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Read the first character of an <code>ls -l</code> line to know the file type: <code>-</code> regular, <code>d</code> directory, <code>l</code> symlink, <code>b</code> block device, <code>c</code> character device, <code>p</code> named pipe, <code>s</code> socket. A symlink line also shows <code>linkname -&gt; target</code>. Hard links share an inode and cannot cross filesystems; symlinks have their own inode and can.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Local User Account Management", body:"<p>Linux is a true multi-user system, and managing accounts is a core administrative duty. Every account has a name, a numeric ID, a home directory, and a login shell, and a small family of commands creates, modifies, and removes them.</p><h3>Creating Accounts: useradd and adduser</h3><p>The low-level, distribution-neutral command is <code>useradd</code>. A typical invocation is <code>useradd -m -s /bin/bash -c 'Jane Doe' jane</code>, where <code>-m</code> creates the home directory, <code>-s</code> sets the login shell, and <code>-c</code> fills the comment (GECOS) field. Without <code>-m</code> on many systems no home directory is created. Useful extras: <code>-u 1500</code> forces a specific UID, <code>-g developers</code> sets the primary group, <code>-G wheel,docker</code> adds supplementary groups at creation, and <code>-r</code> creates a system account below UID 1000. Debian and Ubuntu also ship <code>adduser</code>, a friendlier interactive Perl wrapper that prompts for a password and details and applies sensible defaults. On Red Hat systems <code>adduser</code> is usually just a symlink to <code>useradd</code>. Defaults for new accounts come from <code>/etc/default/useradd</code> and <code>/etc/login.defs</code>.</p><h3>The Login Shell and Skeleton Directory</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>login shell</span> is the program launched when the user logs in, recorded as the last field of their <code>/etc/passwd</code> line. To deny interactive login -- common for service accounts -- set the shell to <code>/usr/sbin/nologin</code> or <code>/bin/false</code>. When <code>useradd -m</code> builds a home directory, it populates it by copying the contents of the <span class='keyterm'>skeleton directory</span> <code>/etc/skel</code>, which holds template dotfiles such as <code>.bashrc</code> and <code>.profile</code>. Editing <code>/etc/skel</code> changes what every future user receives, making it the right place to set organization-wide defaults.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>useradd -m -s /bin/bash jane</code></td><td>Create user with home and bash shell</td></tr><tr><td><code>usermod -aG sudo jane</code></td><td>Add jane to the sudo group (append)</td></tr><tr><td><code>usermod -s /usr/sbin/nologin svc</code></td><td>Change a login shell</td></tr><tr><td><code>usermod -L jane</code></td><td>Lock the account password</td></tr><tr><td><code>userdel jane</code></td><td>Delete the account, keep home</td></tr><tr><td><code>userdel -r jane</code></td><td>Delete account and remove home/mail</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Modifying and Deleting Accounts</h3><p>The <code>usermod</code> command changes existing accounts: <code>-s</code> changes the shell, <code>-d</code> changes the home directory (<code>-m</code> with <code>-d</code> moves the contents), <code>-l</code> renames the login, <code>-u</code> reassigns the UID, and <code>-aG</code> appends supplementary groups. The <code>-a</code> (append) flag is critical -- using <code>-G</code> without <code>-a</code> replaces the user's entire supplementary group list, silently dropping them from groups you forgot to relist. To remove an account, <code>userdel jane</code> deletes the account but leaves the home directory behind, whereas <code>userdel -r jane</code> also deletes the home directory and mail spool. After deleting a user, files they owned elsewhere become orphaned and display a bare numeric UID in <code>ls -l</code>; <code>find / -nouser</code> locates them.</p><h3>UID Ranges and Account Types</h3><p>Every account has a numeric <span class='keyterm'>UID</span>, and the ranges are conventionally partitioned.</p><table><thead><tr><th>UID</th><th>Account type</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>0</code></td><td>root (superuser)</td><td>Unrestricted, always exists</td></tr><tr><td><code>1-999</code></td><td>System / service</td><td>daemon, www-data, sshd; no login</td></tr><tr><td><code>1000+</code></td><td>Regular users</td><td>Real people, start at UID_MIN</td></tr><tr><td><code>65534</code></td><td>nobody</td><td>Unprivileged fallback identity</td></tr></tbody></table><p>UID <code>0</code> is always <span class='keyterm'>root</span>, the superuser. UIDs below 1000 (the <code>UID_MIN</code> in <code>/etc/login.defs</code>) are reserved for <span class='keyterm'>system and service accounts</span> such as <code>daemon</code>, <code>www-data</code>, and <code>sshd</code>, which run background services without interactive login. Regular human <span class='keyterm'>user accounts</span> start at 1000 and climb. A <span class='keyterm'>service account</span> typically has a locked password and a <code>nologin</code> shell, existing only to own files and processes for a daemon while limiting the damage if that daemon is compromised.</p><p>Keeping UIDs consistent across machines matters more than it first appears. Because the filesystem stores numeric ownership, not names, a user with UID 1001 on one host and 1005 on another will appear to own different files when a disk or backup is moved between them -- which is why environments that share storage centralize identity in LDAP or assign UIDs deliberately rather than letting each host auto-increment. The <code>su</code> and <code>sudo</code> commands let an administrator step into another identity: <code>su - jane</code> starts a full login shell as jane (the dash loads her environment), while <code>sudo -u jane command</code> runs a single command as her. Granting administrative rights is best done by adding the account to the <code>sudo</code> group on Debian or <code>wheel</code> on Red Hat rather than sharing the root password, since <code>sudo</code> logs every elevated command to the journal and can be scoped per-command in <code>/etc/sudoers</code>. Never edit <code>/etc/sudoers</code> with a plain editor; use <code>visudo</code>, which validates syntax before saving so a typo cannot lock out all administrative access. When auditing a new system, <code>getent passwd</code> enumerates every account from all configured sources, local and networked alike.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>Always use <code>usermod -aG</code> (append) when adding supplementary groups. Omitting <code>-a</code> turns <code>-G</code> into a replace operation that can remove a user from <code>sudo</code> or other critical groups in a single keystroke.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Groups and the Account Configuration Files", body:"<p>Groups let you grant permissions to many users at once, and the account databases that back them are plain text files you can read directly. Knowing every field of <code>/etc/passwd</code>, <code>/etc/shadow</code>, and <code>/etc/group</code> is essential exam knowledge.</p><h3>Managing Groups</h3><p>Create a group with <code>groupadd developers</code> (add <code>-g 4000</code> to pin the GID, <code>-r</code> for a system group), rename or change its GID with <code>groupmod</code> (<code>groupmod -n devs developers</code> renames, <code>groupmod -g 4100 devs</code> renumbers), and delete it with <code>groupdel developers</code> (which fails if the group is some user's primary group). Add a user to a group with <code>usermod -aG developers jane</code> or <code>gpasswd -a jane developers</code>; remove with <code>gpasswd -d jane developers</code>. The <code>groups jane</code> command lists every group a user belongs to, and the <code>id jane</code> command shows the UID, primary GID, and all supplementary GIDs together, for example <code>uid=1001(jane) gid=1001(jane) groups=1001(jane),27(sudo)</code>.</p><h3>Primary versus Supplementary Groups</h3><p>Each user has exactly one <span class='keyterm'>primary group</span>, recorded by GID in their <code>/etc/passwd</code> line; new files they create are owned by this group by default. A user may also belong to many <span class='keyterm'>supplementary groups</span>, listed in <code>/etc/group</code>, which grant additional access -- membership in <code>sudo</code> or <code>wheel</code> for administration, or a shared project group for collaborative directories. Many distributions follow the <span class='keyterm'>user private group</span> scheme, creating a dedicated group named after each user as their primary group. The <code>newgrp developers</code> command starts a subshell whose effective primary group is temporarily switched, so files created there belong to that group.</p><h3>/etc/passwd and /etc/group</h3><p>The <code>/etc/passwd</code> file holds one line per account with seven colon-separated fields. Despite the name it no longer stores passwords; the second field is just an <code>x</code> placeholder pointing to the shadow file.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Example</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1 username</td><td><code>jane</code></td><td>Login name</td></tr><tr><td>2 password</td><td><code>x</code></td><td>Placeholder; real hash in shadow</td></tr><tr><td>3 UID</td><td><code>1001</code></td><td>Numeric user ID</td></tr><tr><td>4 GID</td><td><code>1001</code></td><td>Primary group ID</td></tr><tr><td>5 GECOS</td><td><code>Jane Doe</code></td><td>Comment / full name</td></tr><tr><td>6 home</td><td><code>/home/jane</code></td><td>Home directory</td></tr><tr><td>7 shell</td><td><code>/bin/bash</code></td><td>Login shell</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>/etc/shadow Fields</h3><p>The <code>/etc/shadow</code> file is readable only by root and holds the real hashed passwords plus aging data, colon-separated. The hash field encodes the algorithm in its <code>$id$</code> prefix -- <code>$6$</code> is SHA-512, <code>$y$</code> is yescrypt; a <code>!</code> or <code>*</code> prefix means locked. The <code>/etc/group</code> file lists each group with four fields: group name, an <code>x</code> password placeholder, the GID, and a comma-separated list of supplementary members. A user's primary group appears in <code>/etc/passwd</code>, not in this member list, which is a common point of confusion.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1 username</td><td>Login name (links to passwd)</td></tr><tr><td>2 password</td><td>Hashed password or <code>!</code>/<code>*</code> lock</td></tr><tr><td>3 last change</td><td>Days since epoch of last change</td></tr><tr><td>4 min</td><td>Minimum days between changes</td></tr><tr><td>5 max</td><td>Maximum password age in days</td></tr><tr><td>6 warn</td><td>Warning days before expiry</td></tr><tr><td>7 inactive</td><td>Grace days after expiry</td></tr><tr><td>8 expire</td><td>Account expiration date</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Editing the Files Safely</h3><p>You can read these files with any tool, but you should never edit <code>/etc/passwd</code> or <code>/etc/shadow</code> directly with a plain text editor, because a second administrator editing simultaneously could overwrite your change and a malformed line can lock everyone out. The correct tool is <code>vipw</code>, which locks the file while you edit it (and <code>vipw -s</code> for the shadow file), and <code>vigr</code> for <code>/etc/group</code>. Better still, use the account commands -- <code>useradd</code>, <code>usermod</code>, <code>groupadd</code>, <code>passwd</code> -- which update all the related files atomically. To check that the databases are internally consistent, <code>pwck</code> verifies <code>/etc/passwd</code> against <code>/etc/shadow</code> while <code>grpck</code> validates <code>/etc/group</code>.</p><p>Reading these files directly is a core troubleshooting skill. Rather than open them in an editor, use <code>getent</code>, which queries the same databases through the system's name-service switch and so works whether the account is local or comes from LDAP: <code>getent passwd jane</code> prints her passwd line, and <code>getent group developers</code> shows a group's membership. When a login mysteriously fails, the first checks are whether the shadow hash is locked (a leading <code>!</code>), whether the account has expired, and whether the shell field points at a real, executable shell rather than <code>/usr/sbin/nologin</code>. A subtle trap is the group-membership cache: adding a user to a group with <code>usermod -aG</code> does not affect sessions that are already open, because supplementary groups are read at login. The user must log out and back in -- or start a fresh login shell -- before the new group takes effect, which routinely confuses people who add themselves to the <code>docker</code> group and then wonder why permission is still denied. Confirm the effective set in the live session with <code>id</code>, and the configured set with <code>groups jane</code>; a discrepancy between the two is the tell-tale sign that a relogin is needed.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Count the fields. <code>/etc/passwd</code> has seven colon-separated fields and is world-readable; <code>/etc/shadow</code> has nine and is root-only. A locked password in <code>/etc/shadow</code> is shown by a leading <code>!</code> or <code>*</code> on the hash field. A user's primary group lives in <code>/etc/passwd</code> by GID, not in the member list of <code>/etc/group</code>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Password Policy and Account Aging", body:"<p>Setting a password is only the beginning; enterprise security demands controlling how long passwords last, when accounts expire, and the ability to lock an account instantly. Linux exposes all of this through <code>passwd</code> and <code>chage</code>, and lets you audit who has logged in.</p><h3>Setting and Locking Passwords with passwd</h3><p>The <code>passwd</code> command changes a password: a regular user runs <code>passwd</code> to change their own, and root runs <code>passwd jane</code> to set another user's. Beyond changing it, <code>passwd -l jane</code> <span class='keyterm'>locks</span> the account by prefixing the stored hash with a <code>!</code> so no password can match, and <code>passwd -u jane</code> unlocks it. <code>passwd -e jane</code> expires the password immediately, forcing a change at next login, and <code>passwd -S jane</code> reports the account's status line. System-wide complexity rules (minimum length, character classes) are enforced through PAM modules such as <code>pam_pwquality</code> configured in <code>/etc/security/pwquality.conf</code>.</p><h3>Account Aging with chage</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>chage</span> (change age) command manages the password-aging fields in <code>/etc/shadow</code>. Run <code>chage -l jane</code> to list all aging information in readable form. Key options set policy:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Option</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>chage -l jane</code></td><td>List aging info for jane</td></tr><tr><td><code>chage -M 90 jane</code></td><td>Password must change every 90 days</td></tr><tr><td><code>chage -m 7 jane</code></td><td>Minimum 7 days between changes</td></tr><tr><td><code>chage -W 14 jane</code></td><td>Warn 14 days before expiry</td></tr><tr><td><code>chage -E 2026-12-31 jane</code></td><td>Account expires on this date</td></tr><tr><td><code>chage -I 30 jane</code></td><td>Lock 30 days after password expires</td></tr><tr><td><code>chage -d 0 jane</code></td><td>Force change at next login</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Locking versus Disabling versus Expiring</h3><p>It is worth separating three related ideas. <span class='keyterm'>Locking</span> the password (<code>usermod -L</code> or <code>passwd -l</code>) prevents password login but leaves SSH-key login possible, since the key bypasses the password. <span class='keyterm'>Expiring</span> the account (<code>chage -E</code> with a past date, or <code>usermod -e</code>) disables the whole account regardless of authentication method. To fully bar interactive access for a service account you combine a locked password with a <code>nologin</code> shell. Use <code>usermod -U</code> to reverse a lock applied with <code>usermod -L</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Action</th><th>Command</th><th>Blocks SSH key?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Lock password</td><td><code>passwd -l</code> / <code>usermod -L</code></td><td>No</td></tr><tr><td>Expire account</td><td><code>chage -E 0</code> / <code>usermod -e</code></td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Disable shell</td><td><code>usermod -s /usr/sbin/nologin</code></td><td>Yes (no shell)</td></tr><tr><td>Force change</td><td><code>chage -d 0</code> / <code>passwd -e</code></td><td>No</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Auditing Logins: lastlog, last, who, w, and whoami</h3><p>Several commands answer the question of who has used the system. <code>whoami</code> prints your own effective username -- handy after a <code>su</code> or <code>sudo</code>. <code>who</code> lists users currently logged in with their terminal and login time, while <code>w</code> goes further, adding system load and what each user is currently running. <code>last</code> reads the <code>/var/log/wtmp</code> binary log to show a history of logins and reboots, and <code>lastlog</code> reports the most recent login time for every account from <code>/var/log/lastlog</code>, making it easy to spot accounts that have never been used. The companion <code>lastb</code> reads <code>/var/log/btmp</code> to show failed login attempts, invaluable when investigating a brute-force attempt.</p><p>Password aging exists to balance two security goals that pull in opposite directions. Forcing changes too often (a low <code>-M</code>) drives users to weak, incrementing passwords and sticky notes, while never expiring credentials lets a leaked password stay valid indefinitely. Modern guidance favors long, unique passphrases with expiry only on suspicion of compromise, but many compliance regimes still mandate a maximum age, which <code>chage -M</code> enforces. The minimum age (<code>-m</code>) deserves a mention because it has a specific defensive purpose: it stops a user who is forced to change their password from immediately cycling back to the old one by changing it several times in a row. The inactivity window (<code>-I</code>) is a grace period -- after the password expires, the user has that many days to log in and set a new one before the account is locked outright. To roll a new policy across every existing human account at once, administrators often script a loop over the output of <code>getent passwd</code>, filtering on UID 1000 and above, and apply <code>chage</code> to each, since editing the defaults in <code>/etc/login.defs</code> only affects accounts created afterward.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Reports</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>whoami</code></td><td>Your current effective user</td></tr><tr><td><code>who</code></td><td>Who is logged in now</td></tr><tr><td><code>w</code></td><td>Logged-in users plus activity and load</td></tr><tr><td><code>last</code></td><td>Login/reboot history (wtmp)</td></tr><tr><td><code>lastlog</code></td><td>Most recent login per account</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>An employee leaves the company. You run <code>usermod -L bob</code> and <code>chage -E 0 bob</code> to lock the password and expire the account today, then <code>usermod -s /usr/sbin/nologin bob</code> so no shell can launch -- a belt-and-suspenders disable that preserves bob's files for handover while blocking every login path, including SSH keys that a mere password lock would leave open.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Process Concepts: PIDs, States, and the Process Tree", body:"<p>A running program is a <span class='keyterm'>process</span>, and the kernel tracks each one with a rich set of attributes. Understanding identifiers, parentage, and states is the foundation for monitoring and controlling everything the system runs.</p><h3>PIDs, PPIDs, and the Process Tree</h3><p>Every process has a unique <span class='keyterm'>PID</span> (process ID), a positive integer assigned at creation, and a <span class='keyterm'>PPID</span> (parent process ID) naming the process that spawned it. This parent-child relationship forms a tree rooted at PID 1, which on modern systems is <code>systemd</code> -- the first userspace process, started by the kernel, and the ancestor of everything else. When a process's parent dies before it does, the orphan is re-parented to PID 1, which adopts and eventually reaps it. Each process also carries a real and effective UID/GID that govern its permissions, which is how a setuid program can run with elevated rights.</p><h3>fork and exec</h3><p>Linux creates new processes through a two-step pattern. The <code>fork()</code> system call duplicates the calling process, producing a near-identical child with its own PID that shares a copy-on-write image of the parent's memory. The child then typically calls <code>exec()</code>, which replaces its memory image with a brand-new program. This <span class='keyterm'>fork-and-exec</span> model is why your shell can launch a command (fork a copy of itself, then exec the target) and wait for it to finish before returning the prompt.</p><h3>Process States</h3><p>At any instant a process is in one of several states, shown in the <code>STAT</code> column of <code>ps</code> and the <code>S</code> column of <code>top</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>State</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>R</td><td>Running / runnable</td><td>Executing or waiting for a CPU</td></tr><tr><td>S</td><td>Interruptible sleep</td><td>Waiting for an event, wakes on signal</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>Uninterruptible sleep</td><td>Waiting on I/O, cannot be interrupted</td></tr><tr><td>T</td><td>Stopped</td><td>Suspended by a signal (Ctrl+Z)</td></tr><tr><td>Z</td><td>Zombie</td><td>Finished but not yet reaped by parent</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Suffixes refine the picture in <code>ps</code>: <code>&lt;</code> high priority, <code>N</code> low priority (niced), <code>s</code> session leader, <code>l</code> multithreaded, and <code>+</code> in the foreground process group.</p><h3>Zombies and Stopped Processes</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>zombie</span> (defunct) process has completed execution but still occupies a slot in the process table because its parent has not yet read its exit status with <code>wait()</code>. Zombies consume no CPU or memory beyond that table entry; a few are harmless, but a flood signals a buggy parent that is not reaping its children. You cannot kill a zombie directly -- you must signal or restart its parent so the entry is collected. A <span class='keyterm'>stopped</span> process has been frozen, usually by Ctrl+Z or a <code>SIGSTOP</code>, and can be resumed with <code>SIGCONT</code>.</p><h3>The /proc Filesystem and pstree</h3><p>The kernel exposes a directory under <code>/proc</code> for every running process, named by its PID.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Path</th><th>Contents</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/proc/PID/status</code></td><td>State, memory, UID in readable form</td></tr><tr><td><code>/proc/PID/cmdline</code></td><td>Exact command line (null-separated)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/proc/PID/cwd</code></td><td>Symlink to working directory</td></tr><tr><td><code>/proc/PID/environ</code></td><td>Environment variables</td></tr><tr><td><code>/proc/PID/fd/</code></td><td>Open file descriptors</td></tr></tbody></table><p>To see the hierarchy visually, <code>pstree</code> draws the entire tree with children indented under their parents, and <code>pstree -p</code> annotates each with its PID -- the fastest way to grasp which process launched which.</p><p>The process model has direct operational consequences. Because a child inherits its parent's open file descriptors, environment, and working directory, a misconfigured environment in a parent shell silently propagates to everything it launches, which is why a service that works when run by hand but fails under systemd often has an environment difference at its root. Daemons traditionally <span class='keyterm'>double-fork</span> and call <code>setsid()</code> to detach from the controlling terminal and become session leaders, so that closing the terminal cannot send them a hangup; under systemd this is usually unnecessary because the manager supervises the process directly with <code>Type=simple</code>. You can read a process's full ancestry by following the <code>PPid</code> field in successive <code>/proc/PID/status</code> files up to PID 1. Resource limits inherited from the parent -- the open-file count, stack size, and process count shown by <code>ulimit -a</code> -- bound what a child can do, and a service that hits the open-file ceiling will fail with confusing errors until the limit is raised in its unit file. Understanding that every process is a node in a single inherited tree, not an island, turns a great deal of puzzling behavior into something predictable.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>You cannot kill a zombie. It is already dead; the fix is to signal its parent (or let the parent exit so PID 1 reaps it). A process stuck in state <code>D</code> (uninterruptible sleep) is blocked on I/O and likewise will not respond to <code>SIGKILL</code> until the I/O completes.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Monitoring Processes: ps, top, htop, and Performance Tools", body:"<p>Knowing what is consuming a server's resources is a daily task. Linux offers a snapshot tool, interactive live dashboards, and finer-grained performance utilities, each suited to a different question.</p><h3>ps: the Snapshot</h3><p>The <code>ps</code> command prints a one-time snapshot of processes. Two flag styles dominate. The BSD style <code>ps aux</code> shows every process for every user with CPU and memory percentages; the UNIX style <code>ps -ef</code> shows a full-format listing including the PPID. Both are worth memorizing because exam questions and real scripts use each. Pipe into <code>grep</code> to filter, as in <code>ps aux | grep nginx</code>, or sort with <code>ps aux --sort=-%mem | head</code> to find memory hogs. For custom columns, <code>ps -eo pid,ppid,ni,stat,comm</code> selects exactly the fields you want.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Column (ps aux)</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>USER</td><td>Account owning the process</td></tr><tr><td>PID</td><td>Process ID</td></tr><tr><td>%CPU / %MEM</td><td>Share of CPU and RAM used</td></tr><tr><td>VSZ / RSS</td><td>Virtual size / resident memory (KB)</td></tr><tr><td>STAT</td><td>Process state code (R, S, D, Z, T)</td></tr><tr><td>START / TIME</td><td>Start time / cumulative CPU time</td></tr><tr><td>COMMAND</td><td>The command and its arguments</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>top and htop: Live Dashboards</h3><p><code>top</code> refreshes a full-screen view every few seconds, ranked by CPU use. Its header shows uptime, the three <span class='keyterm'>load averages</span> (1-, 5-, and 15-minute), total tasks by state, CPU breakdown, and memory and swap usage.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Key in top</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>M</code></td><td>Sort by memory usage</td></tr><tr><td><code>P</code></td><td>Sort by CPU usage</td></tr><tr><td><code>k</code></td><td>Send a signal to a PID</td></tr><tr><td><code>r</code></td><td>Renice a process</td></tr><tr><td><code>1</code></td><td>Show each CPU core separately</td></tr></tbody></table><p><span class='keyterm'>htop</span> is a friendlier enhancement with color bars per core, mouse support, horizontal scrolling to see full command lines, and easy tree and search views -- it usually must be installed separately but is the preferred interactive monitor.</p><h3>Reading Load Average</h3><p>The load average estimates how many processes are runnable or waiting on I/O over an interval. The number is best interpreted relative to CPU count: on a 4-core machine a load of 4.0 means full utilization, while 8.0 means the run queue is twice the cores -- processes are waiting. A 1-minute figure far above the 15-minute figure means load is rising; the reverse means it is easing. Crucially, Linux load includes processes in uninterruptible <code>D</code> state, so a high load can reflect I/O wait rather than CPU saturation.</p><h3>Finer Tools: mpstat, pidstat, and strace</h3><p>For deeper analysis the <span class='keyterm'>sysstat</span> package provides <code>mpstat</code>, which breaks CPU usage down per core (<code>mpstat -P ALL 1</code> updates every second), exposing whether one core is pinned while others idle. <code>pidstat</code> reports per-process statistics over time -- <code>pidstat -p 1234 1</code> shows that PID's CPU, memory, and I/O each second. When you need to know exactly what a process is doing at the kernel boundary, <span class='keyterm'>strace</span> traces its system calls: <code>strace -p 1234</code> attaches to a running process and prints each call, invaluable for diagnosing a program hung on a file or socket. A focused invocation like <code>strace -f -e trace=open,openat -p 1234</code> follows child processes and limits output to file-opening calls, quickly revealing which configuration file a program cannot find.</p><p>Choosing the right monitoring tool is a matter of the question you are asking. If you need a record you can paste into a ticket, the static output of <code>ps</code> is right; if you are hunting a problem as it unfolds, the live refresh of <code>top</code> or <code>htop</code> lets you watch a runaway process climb. For capacity questions -- is this server CPU-bound, memory-bound, or I/O-bound? -- the <code>sysstat</code> tools shine, because they sample over an interval and expose averages rather than an instantaneous flicker. A frequent diagnostic pattern is to start from the load average, confirm with <code>mpstat</code> whether the pressure is genuine CPU work or I/O wait, then drill into the specific offender with <code>pidstat</code> and finally <code>strace</code>. Remember too that <code>top</code> shows memory in two important ways: <span class='keyterm'>RES</span> (resident, actual RAM in use) is what matters for pressure, while <span class='keyterm'>VIRT</span> (virtual) includes mapped-but-unused address space and routinely looks alarmingly large for normal programs. Reading RES, not VIRT, keeps you from chasing phantom memory leaks.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>ps aux</code></td><td>Quick one-time process snapshot</td></tr><tr><td><code>top</code> / <code>htop</code></td><td>Live, sortable resource dashboard</td></tr><tr><td><code>mpstat -P ALL 1</code></td><td>Per-CPU-core utilization over time</td></tr><tr><td><code>pidstat -p PID 1</code></td><td>Per-process CPU/mem/IO over time</td></tr><tr><td><code>strace -p PID</code></td><td>Tracing one process's system calls</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>Interpret load average against core count: divide the load by the number of CPUs from <code>nproc</code> or <code>lscpu</code>. A load of 8 is healthy on a 16-core box and alarming on a 2-core box. And remember Linux load counts I/O-blocked (<code>D</code> state) tasks, so a busy disk can drive load up with idle CPUs.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Controlling Processes: Signals, Priority, and Job Control", body:"<p>Beyond watching processes, you must be able to stop them, restart them, adjust how much CPU they get, and juggle several at once from a single terminal. Signals, scheduling priority, and job control are the three mechanisms.</p><h3>Signals and the kill Family</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>signal</span> is an asynchronous message the kernel delivers to a process, asking it to do something. Despite the name, <code>kill</code> sends any signal, not just a fatal one: <code>kill -TERM 1234</code> or <code>kill 1234</code> sends the default <code>SIGTERM</code>. List all signals with <code>kill -l</code>. The most-tested signals are below.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Signal</th><th>Number</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SIGHUP</td><td>1</td><td>Hang up; many daemons reload config</td></tr><tr><td>SIGINT</td><td>2</td><td>Interrupt (Ctrl+C), polite stop</td></tr><tr><td>SIGKILL</td><td>9</td><td>Force kill, cannot be caught or ignored</td></tr><tr><td>SIGTERM</td><td>15</td><td>Terminate gracefully (default)</td></tr><tr><td>SIGSTOP</td><td>19</td><td>Pause the process (uncatchable)</td></tr><tr><td>SIGCONT</td><td>18</td><td>Resume a stopped process</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Always try <code>SIGTERM</code> first so a program can clean up and flush data; reserve <code>SIGKILL</code> (<code>kill -9</code>) for processes that ignore graceful requests, since it gives no chance to save state. To signal by name rather than PID, <code>killall nginx</code> targets every process matching that exact name, while <code>pkill -f 'python app.py'</code> matches against the full command line and supports patterns. Their read-only sibling <code>pgrep -f pattern</code> lists matching PIDs without signaling.</p><h3>Priority: nice and renice</h3><p>The kernel scheduler uses a <span class='keyterm'>nice value</span> from <code>-20</code> (highest priority, least nice) to <code>+19</code> (lowest priority, most nice) to bias CPU allocation. Launch a program with an adjusted niceness using <code>nice -n 10 backup.sh</code> to run it gently in the background, and change a running process with <code>renice -n 5 -p 1234</code>. Only root can assign a negative (higher-priority) value; ordinary users may only lower their own processes' priority and cannot raise it back. The current niceness appears in the <code>NI</code> column of <code>top</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Niceness</th><th>Priority</th><th>Who can set</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>-20</code></td><td>Highest (greediest)</td><td>root only</td></tr><tr><td><code>0</code></td><td>Default</td><td>Anyone</td></tr><tr><td><code>+19</code></td><td>Lowest (most yielding)</td><td>Anyone (own procs)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Job Control: fg, bg, jobs, and backgrounding</h3><p>A single shell can manage multiple <span class='keyterm'>jobs</span>. Append <code>&amp;</code> to a command (<code>sleep 300 &amp;</code>) to start it in the background and keep the prompt. Press <code>Ctrl+Z</code> to suspend the foreground job, then <code>bg</code> resumes it in the background and <code>fg</code> brings it back to the foreground. The <code>jobs</code> command lists the shell's jobs with their numbers, which you reference as <code>fg %1</code>. These commands operate only within the current shell session.</p><h3>Surviving Logout: nohup and disown</h3><p>By default, closing a terminal sends <code>SIGHUP</code> to its jobs, killing them. To keep a long task running after you disconnect, prefix it with <span class='keyterm'>nohup</span>: <code>nohup ./long-job.sh &amp;</code> ignores the hangup and redirects output to <code>nohup.out</code>. Alternatively, background a running job and detach it from the shell with <code>disown</code> so it is no longer in the job table and survives logout. For long interactive work, terminal multiplexers like <code>tmux</code> or <code>screen</code> achieve the same persistence more flexibly.</p><p>These three mechanisms combine in everyday administration. When a server is sluggish, you might first <code>renice</code> a batch job to <code>+15</code> so it yields CPU to interactive work, then if a process is truly stuck, escalate from a polite <code>kill</code> to <code>kill -9</code>. A subtle but important rule governs which processes you may signal: an ordinary user can only signal processes they own, while root can signal anything, so a permission-denied error from <code>kill</code> usually means the target belongs to another user or to root. Sending a signal to PID <code>-1</code> as root broadcasts it to every process except init -- a foot-gun to be aware of, not a tool to reach for. The <code>SIGHUP</code> convention deserves emphasis because it is widely tested and widely used: many daemons, including <code>nginx</code> and <code>sshd</code>, treat <code>SIGHUP</code> as a request to re-read their configuration without dropping connections, which is why <code>kill -HUP $(pgrep nginx)</code> or the friendlier <code>systemctl reload nginx</code> applies a config change with zero downtime. Always prefer the service manager's reload verb when one exists, since it knows the correct signal for that particular daemon.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Know the difference cold: <code>SIGTERM</code> (15) asks nicely and can be caught for cleanup; <code>SIGKILL</code> (9) is immediate and uncatchable. Try <code>kill 1234</code> first, escalate to <code>kill -9 1234</code> only if the process will not exit. A process in <code>D</code> state ignores even SIGKILL until its I/O finishes.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Scheduling Tasks: cron, at, and anacron", body:"<p>Automation depends on running commands at the right time without a human present. Linux provides recurring schedulers (cron and anacron), a one-shot scheduler (at), and the newer systemd timers.</p><h3>cron and the crontab</h3><p>The classic recurring scheduler is <span class='keyterm'>cron</span>, a daemon that wakes each minute and runs jobs whose time matches. Per-user schedules live in <span class='keyterm'>crontabs</span>, edited with <code>crontab -e</code>, listed with <code>crontab -l</code>, and removed with <code>crontab -r</code>. Use <code>crontab -u jane -e</code> as root to edit another user's. Each line has five time fields followed by the command.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Range</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Minute</td><td>0-59</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Hour</td><td>0-23</td><td>24-hour clock</td></tr><tr><td>Day of month</td><td>1-31</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Month</td><td>1-12</td><td>Or names (jan)</td></tr><tr><td>Day of week</td><td>0-7</td><td>0 and 7 are Sunday</td></tr></tbody></table><p>An asterisk means every value, a slash gives steps (<code>*/15</code> is every fifteenth), commas list values, and a hyphen gives a range. So <code>30 2 * * 1-5 /opt/backup.sh</code> runs at 2:30 AM Monday through Friday, and <code>*/10 * * * * /usr/bin/check.sh</code> runs every ten minutes. There are also handy shortcuts: <code>@daily</code>, <code>@hourly</code>, <code>@reboot</code>, and <code>@weekly</code> replace the five fields entirely.</p><h3>System-Wide cron Directories</h3><p>Beyond per-user crontabs, the system crontab <code>/etc/crontab</code> and files dropped into <code>/etc/cron.d/</code> add a sixth field naming the user to run as. For convenience, scripts placed in <code>/etc/cron.hourly/</code>, <code>/etc/cron.daily/</code>, <code>/etc/cron.weekly/</code>, and <code>/etc/cron.monthly/</code> are run automatically at those intervals -- no crontab syntax required, just an executable script.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Location</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>crontab -e</code></td><td>Per-user schedule</td></tr><tr><td><code>/etc/crontab</code></td><td>System crontab (sixth user field)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/etc/cron.d/</code></td><td>Drop-in system cron files</td></tr><tr><td><code>/etc/cron.daily/</code></td><td>Scripts run once a day</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>anacron: Catching Missed Jobs</h3><p>Plain cron assumes the machine runs continuously; a job scheduled for 2 AM is simply skipped if the system was off. <span class='keyterm'>anacron</span> solves this for laptops and desktops by tracking when each job last ran (in <code>/var/spool/anacron</code>) and running any that are overdue shortly after boot. Configured in <code>/etc/anacrontab</code> with a period in days, a delay, and a command, anacron guarantees daily and weekly maintenance happens even on intermittently powered machines, though with day-level rather than minute-level precision.</p><h3>at: One-Time Scheduling</h3><p>For a task that should run once at a specific future time, <span class='keyterm'>at</span> is the tool. <code>at 23:00</code> opens a prompt where you type commands, or <code>echo 'systemctl restart app' | at now + 1 hour</code> schedules inline. <code>atq</code> lists pending at jobs with their IDs, and <code>atrm 3</code> cancels job number 3. Like cron, access can be restricted with <code>/etc/at.allow</code> and <code>/etc/at.deny</code> (and <code>/etc/cron.allow</code> / <code>/etc/cron.deny</code> for cron).</p><h3>systemd Timers versus cron</h3><p>Modern distributions increasingly use <span class='keyterm'>systemd timers</span> instead of cron. A timer unit (<code>.timer</code>) triggers a matching service unit (<code>.service</code>) and offers advantages cron lacks: integration with the journal for logging, dependency ordering, accurate catch-up via <code>Persistent=true</code>, randomized delays to avoid thundering herds, and resource control through cgroups. List active timers with <code>systemctl list-timers</code>.</p><p>Two operational details trip people up most often. The first is the environment a scheduled job runs in: cron jobs execute with a deliberately minimal environment and a bare <code>PATH</code>, so a command that works at your interactive prompt may fail under cron because it relied on a <code>PATH</code> entry or variable your shell set. The cure is to use absolute paths to every binary and to set any needed variables explicitly at the top of the crontab. The second is output handling: cron mails a job's standard output and error to the owner by default, and on a system without working mail this silently piles up, so production jobs almost always redirect output to a log file with something like <code>&gt;&gt;/var/log/job.log 2&gt;&amp;1</code>. To verify a schedule fired at all, check the system log -- <code>journalctl -u cron</code> or <code>grep CRON /var/log/syslog</code> shows each invocation. When debugging a job that never seems to run, confirm the crontab is installed for the right user (a job in root's crontab and one in a user crontab behave differently), that the file ends in a newline, and that the day-of-month and day-of-week fields are not combined in a way that ANDs instead of ORs as you expect.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Use when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>cron</code></td><td>Always-on server, recurring jobs</td></tr><tr><td><code>anacron</code></td><td>Machine sometimes off, day precision</td></tr><tr><td><code>at</code></td><td>Single future run</td></tr><tr><td>systemd timer</td><td>Logging, dependencies, catch-up</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>The five crontab fields are minute, hour, day-of-month, month, day-of-week, in that order. Both <code>0</code> and <code>7</code> mean Sunday in the day-of-week field. Use <code>anacron</code> when a machine is not always on, because cron silently skips jobs whose time passed while powered off.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Package Management I: the RPM Family", body:"<p>Software on Linux is distributed as <span class='keyterm'>packages</span> -- archives bundling binaries, libraries, configuration, and metadata describing dependencies. The Red Hat lineage uses the RPM format, managed by a high-level resolver and a low-level tool.</p><h3>Why Package Managers Exist</h3><p>A package records exactly which files it installs, what other packages it requires, and how to remove itself cleanly. This metadata is what lets a package manager resolve <span class='keyterm'>dependencies</span> automatically: when you ask for a web server, it pulls in the libraries that server needs. Without this, you would chase missing libraries by hand -- the dreaded dependency hell that package managers were invented to end.</p><h3>dnf and yum: the High-Level Tools</h3><p>On Fedora, RHEL, Rocky, and AlmaLinux the modern manager is <span class='keyterm'>dnf</span> (Dandified YUM), which replaced the older <code>yum</code>; the <code>yum</code> command still exists as a symlink for compatibility. <code>dnf</code> talks to repositories, downloads packages and their dependencies, and installs them in one transaction.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>dnf install httpd</code></td><td>Install package and dependencies</td></tr><tr><td><code>dnf remove httpd</code></td><td>Remove a package</td></tr><tr><td><code>dnf update</code></td><td>Update all packages</td></tr><tr><td><code>dnf search keyword</code></td><td>Search repository metadata</td></tr><tr><td><code>dnf info httpd</code></td><td>Show package details</td></tr><tr><td><code>dnf provides /usr/sbin/httpd</code></td><td>Find which package owns a file</td></tr><tr><td><code>dnf history</code></td><td>List and undo past transactions</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>rpm: the Low-Level Tool</h3><p>Beneath <code>dnf</code> sits <span class='keyterm'>rpm</span>, which operates on individual <code>.rpm</code> files and the local package database but does <em>not</em> resolve dependencies from repositories. Its query mode (<code>-q</code>) is heavily used: <code>rpm -qa</code> lists all installed packages, <code>rpm -qi httpd</code> shows information, <code>rpm -ql httpd</code> lists the files a package installed, and <code>rpm -qf /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf</code> reveals which package owns a given file. To install a local file use <code>rpm -i pkg.rpm</code> (or <code>-U</code> to upgrade), and to erase use <code>rpm -e pkg</code>. The <code>-V</code> verify mode compares installed files against the database to detect tampering or corruption.</p><table><thead><tr><th>rpm flag</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>-q</code></td><td>Query installed packages</td></tr><tr><td><code>-qa</code></td><td>Query all installed</td></tr><tr><td><code>-qf FILE</code></td><td>Which package owns FILE</td></tr><tr><td><code>-ql PKG</code></td><td>List files in PKG</td></tr><tr><td><code>-i / -U</code></td><td>Install / upgrade a local rpm</td></tr><tr><td><code>-e</code></td><td>Erase (remove) a package</td></tr><tr><td><code>-V</code></td><td>Verify files against the database</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>RPM versus dnf at a Glance</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Capability</th><th>rpm</th><th>dnf</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Resolves dependencies</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Talks to repositories</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Installs local .rpm file</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Queries owned files</td><td>Yes</td><td>Via provides</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Troubleshooting Dependency Problems</h3><p>When <code>rpm -i</code> fails with a list of missing libraries, the cause is that <code>rpm</code> does not fetch dependencies -- the fix is to install through <code>dnf</code> instead, which resolves them from configured repositories. If a transaction is interrupted, <code>dnf check</code> reports problems and <code>rpm --rebuilddb</code> can repair a corrupted database. Forcing an install with <code>rpm --force --nodeps</code> bypasses safety checks and is a last resort that frequently creates the very breakage it appears to avoid. When a package will not update because of a held or duplicate version, <code>dnf distro-sync</code> realigns everything to the repository's expected versions.</p><p>It helps to keep the layering straight. The high-level tool (<code>dnf</code>) is what you reach for nearly always, because it resolves and downloads dependencies; the low-level tool (<code>rpm</code>) is for querying the local database and for the rare case of inspecting or installing a single file you already have on disk. Querying is where <code>rpm</code> earns its keep daily: when a configuration file behaves unexpectedly, <code>rpm -qf /path/to/file</code> tells you which package owns it and therefore where the documentation and defaults live, and <code>rpm -qc httpd</code> lists just the configuration files a package ships so you know exactly what you might need to back up before an upgrade. Updates can be made safer with <code>dnf upgrade --security</code>, which restricts the transaction to security errata, and the entire system's update history is auditable through <code>dnf history</code>, whose <code>undo</code> subcommand can reverse a specific transaction if a patch causes a regression. On RHEL-family systems the same packages may also be offered as <span class='keyterm'>modules</span> with multiple streams, switched with <code>dnf module enable</code>, which lets one release ship several major versions of a language runtime side by side. Knowing these query and history features turns package management from a blind install-and-hope into an auditable, reversible process.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A teammate hands you a single <code>.rpm</code> and <code>rpm -i</code> complains about three missing libraries. Rather than chase each one, you run <code>dnf install ./app.rpm</code>; dnf reads the same package, resolves the three dependencies from the repos, and installs all four in one transaction.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Package Management II: the Debian Family and Language Managers", body:"<p>The other great packaging lineage is Debian's, used by Debian, Ubuntu, and Mint. Beyond the OS package system, developers rely on language-specific managers and sometimes compile software directly from source.</p><h3>apt and apt-get: the High-Level Tools</h3><p>The modern front end is <span class='keyterm'>apt</span>, which unifies and prettifies the older <code>apt-get</code> and <code>apt-cache</code> commands; <code>apt-get</code> remains preferred in scripts for its stable output. apt reads repository lists, downloads <code>.deb</code> packages with their dependencies, and installs them. Crucially, run <code>apt update</code> first to refresh the local package index from the repositories -- this only updates metadata -- then <code>apt upgrade</code> to actually install newer versions.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>apt update</code></td><td>Refresh the package index (metadata)</td></tr><tr><td><code>apt upgrade</code></td><td>Install available updates</td></tr><tr><td><code>apt install apache2</code></td><td>Install a package and dependencies</td></tr><tr><td><code>apt remove apache2</code></td><td>Remove a package, keep config</td></tr><tr><td><code>apt purge apache2</code></td><td>Remove package and its config</td></tr><tr><td><code>apt autoremove</code></td><td>Remove now-unneeded dependencies</td></tr><tr><td><code>apt search keyword</code></td><td>Search available packages</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>dpkg: the Low-Level Tool</h3><p>Underneath apt is <span class='keyterm'>dpkg</span>, which manipulates individual <code>.deb</code> files without resolving dependencies -- the direct counterpart of <code>rpm</code>. Install a local file with <code>dpkg -i pkg.deb</code>, list installed packages with <code>dpkg -l</code>, remove with <code>dpkg -r pkg</code> (or <code>-P</code> to purge config too), and find which package owns a file with <code>dpkg -S /usr/bin/curl</code>; list a package's files with <code>dpkg -L pkg</code>. When <code>dpkg -i</code> leaves unmet dependencies, the standard repair is <code>apt install -f</code> (fix-broken), which pulls in what is missing.</p><table><thead><tr><th>RPM world</th><th>Debian equivalent</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>dnf install</code></td><td><code>apt install</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>rpm -i file.rpm</code></td><td><code>dpkg -i file.deb</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>rpm -qf FILE</code></td><td><code>dpkg -S FILE</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>rpm -ql PKG</code></td><td><code>dpkg -L PKG</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>rpm -qa</code></td><td><code>dpkg -l</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Language-Specific Package Managers</h3><p>Programming ecosystems ship their own managers that install libraries into language-specific locations, separate from the OS package system. <span class='keyterm'>pip</span> installs Python packages from PyPI (<code>pip install requests</code>), ideally inside a virtual environment to avoid polluting the system Python. <span class='keyterm'>npm</span> installs JavaScript packages from the npm registry for Node.js (<code>npm install express</code>, with <code>-g</code> for global). <span class='keyterm'>cargo</span> builds and installs Rust crates (<code>cargo install ripgrep</code>). These coexist with apt or dnf but are not tracked by them, so security updates for language packages are your responsibility.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Manager</th><th>Language</th><th>Install command</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>pip</td><td>Python</td><td><code>pip install NAME</code></td></tr><tr><td>npm</td><td>JavaScript / Node</td><td><code>npm install NAME</code></td></tr><tr><td>cargo</td><td>Rust</td><td><code>cargo install NAME</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Building from Source</h3><p>When software is not packaged, you compile it from source. The classic sequence is <code>./configure</code> (a script that checks for required libraries and headers and generates a Makefile tailored to your system), then <code>make</code> (which compiles the code using that Makefile), then <code>sudo make install</code> (which copies the resulting binaries into place, often under <code>/usr/local</code>). You typically need a toolchain first -- the <code>build-essential</code> meta-package on Debian or the <code>Development Tools</code> group on Red Hat -- plus the <code>-dev</code>/<code>-devel</code> header packages for any libraries the program links against. Software installed this way is invisible to apt and dnf, so you uninstall it with <code>make uninstall</code> if the project provides that target.</p><p>The Debian and Red Hat worlds map onto each other closely enough that learning one teaches most of the other, but a few differences matter. The two-step apt workflow -- <code>update</code> then <code>upgrade</code> -- has no exact dnf parallel, because dnf refreshes its metadata automatically before each transaction; forgetting <code>apt update</code> is the single most common apt mistake, leaving you to install yesterday's versions or hit a download error for a package the stale index still points at. On the cleanup side, <code>apt autoremove</code> prunes dependencies that were pulled in automatically and are no longer needed, the counterpart to <code>dnf autoremove</code>. Language managers introduce their own hazard: running <code>pip install</code> as root into the system Python can overwrite files that the OS package manager believes it owns, leading to conflicts that are painful to untangle, which is precisely why virtual environments (<code>python -m venv</code>) and per-user installs (<code>pip install --user</code>) are strongly preferred. The newer <span class='keyterm'>pipx</span> tool installs Python applications each in their own isolated environment while exposing their commands on the PATH, neatly sidestepping the whole class of conflicts. Whatever the source, the cardinal rule is to track what you installed and how, so that another administrator -- or you in six months -- can reproduce or remove it.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Always run <code>apt update</code> before <code>apt upgrade</code>: the first refreshes the metadata index, the second installs newer packages. Remember the build-from-source trio in order -- <code>./configure</code>, <code>make</code>, <code>make install</code> -- and that <code>dpkg</code>/<code>rpm</code> do not resolve dependencies while <code>apt</code>/<code>dnf</code> do.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Repositories and Sandboxed Applications", body:"<p>Packages come from <span class='keyterm'>repositories</span> -- servers hosting signed collections of software. Managing which repositories a system trusts, and layering in sandboxed application formats, are both part of keeping a system supplied and secure.</p><h3>Repository Configuration Files</h3><p>On the RPM family, repositories are defined in <code>.repo</code> files under <code>/etc/yum.repos.d/</code>. Each stanza names the repo, gives a <code>baseurl</code> or <code>mirrorlist</code>, an <code>enabled=1</code> flag, and <code>gpgcheck=1</code> with the path to its signing key. On the Debian family, repositories live in <code>/etc/apt/sources.list</code> and individual files under <code>/etc/apt/sources.list.d/</code>, each a <code>deb</code> line naming the URL, distribution codename, and components.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Family</th><th>Repo config location</th><th>Enable/disable</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>RPM (dnf)</td><td><code>/etc/yum.repos.d/*.repo</code></td><td><code>dnf config-manager --enable NAME</code></td></tr><tr><td>Debian (apt)</td><td><code>/etc/apt/sources.list.d/*</code></td><td>Comment the line / <code>add-apt-repository</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Enabling and Disabling Repositories</h3><p>You can toggle a repository without deleting its file. With dnf, <code>dnf config-manager --enable powertools</code> turns one on and <code>--disable</code> turns it off; you can also enable a repo for a single transaction with <code>dnf --enablerepo=epel install pkg</code>. On Debian, <code>add-apt-repository ppa:user/ppa</code> adds a Personal Package Archive, and you disable a source simply by commenting out its line and re-running <code>apt update</code>. Third-party repositories (EPEL on Red Hat, PPAs on Ubuntu) extend the catalog beyond the base distribution. List configured repos with <code>dnf repolist</code>.</p><h3>GPG Keys and Trust</h3><p>Packages are cryptographically signed so the manager can verify they came from the stated repository and were not tampered with in transit. Each repository's <span class='keyterm'>GPG public key</span> must be imported before its packages are trusted. On RPM systems you import with <code>rpm --import KEYFILE</code>; on Debian the modern practice stores keys in <code>/etc/apt/keyrings/</code> referenced by a <code>signed-by=</code> option in the source line. If a key is missing or wrong, the manager refuses the package with a signature error -- a deliberate safety stop, not a bug to bypass with <code>--nogpgcheck</code>.</p><h3>Flatpak and Snap: Sandboxed Applications</h3><p>Two modern formats distribute applications with their dependencies bundled and run them in a <span class='keyterm'>sandbox</span> isolated from the rest of the system. <span class='keyterm'>Flatpak</span> pulls apps from remotes such as Flathub (<code>flatpak install flathub org.gimp.GIMP</code>, run with <code>flatpak run</code>); it shares runtimes between apps to save space and gates filesystem and device access through portals. <span class='keyterm'>Snap</span>, from Canonical, packages apps as compressed images mounted as loop devices, managed by <code>snap install NAME</code> and the <code>snapd</code> daemon, with automatic background updates. Both let you run the latest version of an app regardless of the base distribution's age, at the cost of larger downloads and some startup overhead.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Flatpak</th><th>Snap</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Default store</td><td>Flathub</td><td>Snap Store</td></tr><tr><td>Backed by</td><td>Community / freedesktop</td><td>Canonical</td></tr><tr><td>Install</td><td><code>flatpak install</code></td><td><code>snap install</code></td></tr><tr><td>Packaging</td><td>Shared runtimes</td><td>SquashFS loop image</td></tr><tr><td>Isolation</td><td>Sandbox via portals</td><td>Confinement via AppArmor</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Distro Packages versus Sandboxed Formats</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Trait</th><th>apt / dnf</th><th>Flatpak / Snap</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Shares system libraries</td><td>Yes</td><td>No (bundled)</td></tr><tr><td>Disk footprint</td><td>Smaller</td><td>Larger</td></tr><tr><td>Isolation</td><td>None</td><td>Sandboxed</td></tr><tr><td>Version freshness</td><td>Tied to distro</td><td>Usually latest</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Basic Service Configuration After Install</h3><p>Installing a service package rarely finishes the job: you typically edit its configuration under <code>/etc/</code>, then enable and start it with systemd (<code>systemctl enable --now httpd</code>). A package may ship a default config that is safe but not useful until tuned, so the install-configure-enable-start sequence is the standard pattern.</p><p>Repository hygiene is a quiet but important security discipline. Every additional repository you trust is another party whose signing key can install software as root, so the rule of thumb is to enable only repositories you genuinely need and to remove or disable the rest. Third-party repos such as EPEL and PPAs are enormously useful for software the base distribution omits, but they can also introduce packages that conflict with or shadow the official ones, which is why <code>dnf</code> supports per-package priorities and why pinning in <code>/etc/apt/preferences.d/</code> exists -- to keep a third-party repo from silently replacing a core system package. When troubleshooting an install that pulls an unexpected version, <code>dnf repoquery --whatprovides NAME</code> on the RPM side, or <code>apt policy NAME</code> on the Debian side, shows every repository offering that package and which one wins, making the source of a surprise immediately visible. Sandboxed formats change the trust picture again: a Flatpak or Snap app runs confined, so even a malicious or buggy one is limited by its sandbox to the directories and devices its manifest declares, reviewable with <code>flatpak info --show-permissions</code>. This containment is the chief security argument for the sandboxed formats over a traditional package that, once installed, runs with the full privileges of whoever launches it.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>A repository's GPG key must be imported before its packages will install. A signature error usually means a missing or mismatched key -- import the correct key rather than disabling verification with <code>--nogpgcheck</code>, which removes the protection entirely.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"systemd Fundamentals: Units, Services, and Targets", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>systemd</span> is the init system and service manager that runs as PID 1 on virtually every modern Linux distribution. It starts services in parallel based on dependencies, tracks them in cgroups, and replaces the older SysV init scripts and runlevels.</p><h3>Units and Unit Files</h3><p>Everything systemd manages is a <span class='keyterm'>unit</span>, described by a unit file. Types include <code>.service</code> (a daemon), <code>.target</code> (a group of units, like a runlevel), <code>.mount</code> (a filesystem), <code>.timer</code> (a scheduled trigger), and <code>.socket</code> (a listening socket). Distribution-provided unit files live in <code>/usr/lib/systemd/system/</code>, while administrator overrides and custom units go in <code>/etc/systemd/system/</code>, which takes precedence. A clean override of just a few directives is best made with <code>systemctl edit unit</code>, which creates a drop-in file under <code>/etc/systemd/system/unit.d/</code> rather than copying the whole file.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Unit type</th><th>Manages</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>.service</code></td><td>A daemon or process</td></tr><tr><td><code>.target</code></td><td>A group of units (runlevel)</td></tr><tr><td><code>.mount</code></td><td>A filesystem mount point</td></tr><tr><td><code>.timer</code></td><td>A scheduled trigger</td></tr><tr><td><code>.socket</code></td><td>A listening socket</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Anatomy of a Service Unit</h3><p>A <code>.service</code> file is an INI-style file with three common sections. <code>[Unit]</code> holds metadata and ordering directives like <code>Description=</code>, <code>After=</code>, and <code>Requires=</code>. <code>[Service]</code> defines how to run the daemon: <code>ExecStart=</code> is the command, <code>Restart=on-failure</code> sets restart policy, <code>User=</code> sets the account, and <code>Type=</code> describes startup behavior (<code>simple</code>, <code>forking</code>, <code>notify</code>). <code>[Install]</code> defines enablement, chiefly <code>WantedBy=multi-user.target</code>, which is what links the service into the boot sequence when you enable it.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Section</th><th>Key directives</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>[Unit]</code></td><td>Description, After, Requires, Wants</td></tr><tr><td><code>[Service]</code></td><td>ExecStart, ExecReload, Restart, User, Type</td></tr><tr><td><code>[Install]</code></td><td>WantedBy, RequiredBy</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Driving Services with systemctl</h3><p>The control command is <span class='keyterm'>systemctl</span>. The everyday verbs are below. Note the key distinction: <code>start</code>/<code>stop</code> act now and do not persist across reboot, while <code>enable</code>/<code>disable</code> set whether the unit launches at boot but do not change its current state -- combine them with <code>enable --now</code> to do both.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>systemctl start sshd</code></td><td>Start now</td></tr><tr><td><code>systemctl stop sshd</code></td><td>Stop now</td></tr><tr><td><code>systemctl enable sshd</code></td><td>Start at every boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>systemctl disable sshd</code></td><td>Do not start at boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>systemctl status sshd</code></td><td>Show state, PID, recent log lines</td></tr><tr><td><code>systemctl restart sshd</code></td><td>Stop then start</td></tr><tr><td><code>systemctl reload sshd</code></td><td>Reload config without full restart</td></tr><tr><td><code>systemctl mask sshd</code></td><td>Make it impossible to start</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Masking and Reloading the Daemon</h3><p><code>systemctl mask</code> goes beyond disable: it symlinks the unit to <code>/dev/null</code> so it cannot be started even manually or as a dependency -- useful to firmly prevent a conflicting service from ever running. Reverse it with <code>unmask</code>. Whenever you create or edit a unit file by hand, you must run <code>systemctl daemon-reload</code> so systemd re-reads the unit definitions; forgetting this is the most common reason an edited unit appears to have no effect.</p><h3>Targets versus Runlevels</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>target</span> groups units to bring the system to a state, replacing SysV runlevels.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Target</th><th>Old runlevel</th><th>State</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>poweroff.target</code></td><td>0</td><td>Shut down</td></tr><tr><td><code>rescue.target</code></td><td>1</td><td>Single-user maintenance</td></tr><tr><td><code>multi-user.target</code></td><td>3</td><td>Text, full networking</td></tr><tr><td><code>graphical.target</code></td><td>5</td><td>Adds the GUI</td></tr><tr><td><code>reboot.target</code></td><td>6</td><td>Reboot</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Switch immediately with <code>systemctl isolate multi-user.target</code> and set the boot default with <code>systemctl set-default graphical.target</code>.</p><p>Reading a service's state fluently is the heart of day-to-day systemd work. The output of <code>systemctl status sshd</code> packs in the essentials: the <span class='keyterm'>Loaded</span> line tells you the unit file path and whether it is enabled at boot, the <span class='keyterm'>Active</span> line reports the runtime state (<code>active (running)</code>, <code>inactive (dead)</code>, or <code>failed</code>) with a timestamp, the main PID and cgroup are shown, and the last several journal lines are appended so a crash reason is often visible without a separate command. When a unit has failed, <code>systemctl reset-failed</code> clears the failed flag after you have addressed the cause, and <code>systemctl list-units --failed</code> surveys everything currently broken. Dependency relationships are inspectable too: <code>systemctl list-dependencies graphical.target</code> expands the tree of what a target pulls in, which demystifies why enabling one service silently started another. The distinction between <code>Wants=</code> (a soft dependency that is tried but not required) and <code>Requires=</code> (a hard dependency whose failure fails the dependent unit) governs how robustly services start, and <code>After=</code> orders startup without implying a dependency at all. Internalizing that ordering and requirement are separate concerns explains a surprising amount of boot behavior.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><code>start</code> affects the running system now; <code>enable</code> affects boot. They are independent -- a service can be enabled but stopped, or running but not enabled. After editing any unit file, run <code>systemctl daemon-reload</code> before the change takes effect.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"systemd Timers, Mounts, and the Journal", body:"<p>Beyond services and targets, systemd manages scheduled jobs, filesystem mounts, and a unified log. It also bundles utilities for time, kernel tuning, and boot analysis that every administrator uses.</p><h3>Timer Units</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>timer unit</span> (<code>.timer</code>) triggers a service unit of the same base name on a schedule, the systemd-native alternative to cron. Two scheduling styles exist. Calendar-based timers use <code>OnCalendar=</code> with a flexible syntax, for example <code>OnCalendar=*-*-* 02:30:00</code> for daily at 2:30 AM or <code>OnCalendar=Mon *-*-* 06:00:00</code> for Mondays. Monotonic timers fire relative to an event: <code>OnBootSec=15min</code> runs 15 minutes after boot, <code>OnUnitActiveSec=1h</code> runs an hour after the last activation. Adding <code>Persistent=true</code> makes a missed timer catch up at next boot. List all timers and their next run with <code>systemctl list-timers</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Directive</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>OnCalendar=daily</code></td><td>Run once a day (00:00)</td></tr><tr><td><code>OnBootSec=15min</code></td><td>Run 15 min after boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>OnUnitActiveSec=1h</code></td><td>Run 1 h after last run</td></tr><tr><td><code>Persistent=true</code></td><td>Catch up if a run was missed</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Mount Units</h3><p>systemd can mount filesystems with <code>.mount</code> units whose filename encodes the mount point (<code>data.mount</code> for <code>/data</code>). In practice most mounts are still declared in <code>/etc/fstab</code>, which systemd reads and converts into mount units automatically. The companion <code>.automount</code> unit mounts a filesystem on first access, useful for network shares you do not want to block boot. When you hand-write a mount unit, the <code>What=</code> directive names the device or source, <code>Where=</code> names the mount point (which must match the filename), and <code>Type=</code> and <code>Options=</code> mirror the corresponding <code>/etc/fstab</code> columns. After adding either an fstab entry or a mount unit you can apply it without rebooting by running <code>systemctl daemon-reload</code> then <code>systemctl start data.mount</code>, or simply <code>mount -a</code> for fstab entries.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Mount unit directive</th><th>fstab column</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>What=</code></td><td>Device / source</td></tr><tr><td><code>Where=</code></td><td>Mount point</td></tr><tr><td><code>Type=</code></td><td>Filesystem type</td></tr><tr><td><code>Options=</code></td><td>Mount options</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>journalctl: the systemd Journal</h3><p>systemd collects all service and kernel logs into a structured binary <span class='keyterm'>journal</span>, queried with <span class='keyterm'>journalctl</span>. Its filters are essential to memorize: <code>journalctl -u sshd</code> shows one unit's logs, <code>-b</code> limits to the current boot (<code>-b -1</code> the previous one), <code>-p err</code> filters by priority, <code>--since '1 hour ago'</code> bounds by time, and <code>-f</code> follows live like <code>tail -f</code>. By default the journal is volatile (lost on reboot) unless <code>/var/log/journal</code> exists to make it persistent; manage its size with <code>journalctl --vacuum-size=500M</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Shows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>journalctl -u nginx</code></td><td>Logs for the nginx unit</td></tr><tr><td><code>journalctl -b</code></td><td>Logs since current boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>journalctl -p err</code></td><td>Error-priority and worse</td></tr><tr><td><code>journalctl --since today</code></td><td>Today's logs</td></tr><tr><td><code>journalctl -f</code></td><td>Follow new entries live</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>sysctl, timedatectl, and systemd-analyze</h3><p>A trio of utilities round out system management. <code>sysctl</code> reads and sets kernel parameters at runtime (<code>sysctl -w net.ipv4.ip_forward=1</code>), with persistent values in <code>/etc/sysctl.d/</code>. <span class='keyterm'>timedatectl</span> manages the clock and time zone: <code>timedatectl set-timezone America/New_York</code> and <code>timedatectl set-ntp true</code> to enable network time sync. <span class='keyterm'>systemd-analyze</span> profiles boot performance -- <code>systemd-analyze blame</code> ranks units by how long they took to start, and <code>systemd-analyze critical-chain</code> shows the dependency path that gated boot.</p><p>The journal repays a little fluency with enormous time savings during an incident. Beyond unit and priority filters, you can pivot on almost any field: <code>journalctl _PID=1234</code> shows everything a specific process logged, <code>journalctl _UID=1001</code> everything a user's processes emitted, and <code>journalctl /usr/sbin/sshd</code> everything from a particular executable. Priorities run from <code>emerg</code> (0) down through <code>err</code> (3) to <code>debug</code> (7), and <code>-p err</code> means that level and worse. Output is paged by default; add <code>--no-pager</code> when capturing to a file, <code>-o json</code> when feeding a log pipeline, or <code>-x</code> to interleave explanatory catalog text that suggests likely causes for known messages. A persistent journal -- enabled simply by creating <code>/var/log/journal</code> and running <code>systemctl restart systemd-journald</code> -- survives reboots, so you can inspect the previous boot's failure with <code>-b -1</code> after a crash, which a volatile journal would have discarded. For mounts, remember the chain of conversion: an entry in <code>/etc/fstab</code> becomes a generated <code>.mount</code> unit, so <code>systemctl status data.mount</code> reports on an fstab line just as it would a hand-written unit, unifying the two mechanisms under one status interface.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A service crashed overnight and you need the evidence. <code>journalctl -u app.service -b -p err --since '2026-06-29 00:00'</code> narrows to error-level entries for that unit, this boot, since midnight -- turning a wall of logs into the handful of lines that matter.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Containers: Podman, Docker, Images, and Networking", body:"<p>Containers package an application with its dependencies into a portable, isolated unit, and they have become central to modern deployment. Linux+ expects familiarity with the runtimes, image lifecycle, and networking.</p><h3>Containers versus Virtual Machines</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>virtual machine</span> runs a full guest operating system on top of a hypervisor, each VM carrying its own kernel -- strong isolation but heavy. A <span class='keyterm'>container</span> instead shares the host kernel and isolates processes using kernel features (<span class='keyterm'>namespaces</span> for visibility and <span class='keyterm'>cgroups</span> for resource limits). Containers are far lighter and faster to start, but provide weaker isolation since the kernel is shared.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Virtual machine</th><th>Container</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Kernel</td><td>Own guest kernel</td><td>Shares host kernel</td></tr><tr><td>Size / startup</td><td>Gigabytes / minutes</td><td>Megabytes / seconds</td></tr><tr><td>Isolation</td><td>Strong (hypervisor)</td><td>Lighter (namespaces)</td></tr><tr><td>Density</td><td>Lower</td><td>Higher</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Runtimes: Podman and Docker</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Docker</span> popularized containers and uses a central daemon (<code>dockerd</code>) that runs as root. <span class='keyterm'>Podman</span>, favored on Red Hat systems, is daemonless and supports <span class='keyterm'>rootless</span> containers run by ordinary users, improving security. Their command syntax is deliberately compatible -- on many systems <code>docker</code> is an alias for <code>podman</code> -- so the verbs below apply to both. Inspect running containers with <code>podman ps</code>, view logs with <code>podman logs NAME</code>, and open a shell inside one with <code>podman exec -it NAME bash</code>.</p><h3>Image Operations</h3><p>A container runs from an <span class='keyterm'>image</span>, a read-only template built in layers. <code>podman pull nginx:latest</code> downloads an image from a registry such as Docker Hub or quay.io; <code>podman images</code> lists local images; <code>podman build -t myapp .</code> builds one from a Dockerfile in the current directory; and <code>podman image prune</code> reclaims space by deleting dangling, unreferenced layers.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>podman pull IMG</code></td><td>Download an image from a registry</td></tr><tr><td><code>podman images</code></td><td>List local images</td></tr><tr><td><code>podman build -t NAME .</code></td><td>Build from a Dockerfile</td></tr><tr><td><code>podman run IMG</code></td><td>Create and start a container</td></tr><tr><td><code>podman ps -a</code></td><td>List all containers</td></tr><tr><td><code>podman rmi IMG</code></td><td>Remove an image</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The Dockerfile</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>Dockerfile</span> is the recipe for an image. <code>FROM</code> sets the base image (the first instruction), <code>RUN</code> executes build commands in a new layer, <code>COPY</code> brings files in, <code>EXPOSE</code> documents a port, <code>USER</code> drops to a non-root account for the running container (an important hardening step), and <code>CMD</code> or <code>ENTRYPOINT</code> defines what runs at launch. Each instruction adds a cached layer, so ordering them from least- to most-frequently-changed speeds rebuilds.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Instruction</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>FROM</code></td><td>Base image (must be first)</td></tr><tr><td><code>RUN</code></td><td>Execute a build command, new layer</td></tr><tr><td><code>COPY</code></td><td>Copy files into the image</td></tr><tr><td><code>EXPOSE</code></td><td>Document a listening port</td></tr><tr><td><code>USER</code></td><td>Drop to a non-root user</td></tr><tr><td><code>CMD</code> / <code>ENTRYPOINT</code></td><td>Default command at launch</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Running, Storage, and Networking</h3><p>You start a container with <code>podman run</code>. Common flags: <code>-d</code> detaches it to the background, <code>-p 8080:80</code> maps host port 8080 to container port 80, <code>-v /host/data:/data</code> mounts a host directory as a <span class='keyterm'>volume</span> for persistent storage, <code>-e KEY=val</code> sets an environment variable, and <code>--name web</code> labels it. Without a volume, data written inside the container lives only in its ephemeral writable <span class='keyterm'>overlay</span> layer and vanishes when the container is removed. Networking offers several drivers.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Network mode</th><th>Behavior</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>bridge</code></td><td>Default; private virtual network, needs port mapping</td></tr><tr><td><code>host</code></td><td>Shares the host's network stack directly, no mapping</td></tr><tr><td><code>overlay</code></td><td>Spans multiple hosts for clustered/swarm setups</td></tr><tr><td><code>none</code></td><td>No networking at all</td></tr></tbody></table><p>With the default <span class='keyterm'>bridge</span> network, a container is on a private subnet and reachable only through the ports you publish with <code>-p</code>. In <span class='keyterm'>host</span> mode the container uses the host's interfaces directly, so a service listening on port 80 is immediately on the host's port 80 with no mapping. An <span class='keyterm'>overlay</span> network connects containers across several hosts, the foundation of orchestrated clusters.</p><p>The image-and-layer model has practical implications worth internalizing. Because each Dockerfile instruction creates a cached layer, a build that copies source code before installing dependencies will needlessly reinstall dependencies on every code change; ordering the <code>COPY</code> of dependency manifests and the <code>RUN</code> that installs them before the <code>COPY</code> of application code lets the dependency layer stay cached across most rebuilds. Tags are mutable pointers, not immutable identities -- <code>nginx:latest</code> today may differ from <code>nginx:latest</code> next week -- so production deployments pin a specific version tag or, more rigorously, a content-addressed <span class='keyterm'>digest</span> to guarantee reproducibility. Security hardening centers on a few habits: build from a minimal base image to shrink the attack surface, add a <code>USER</code> instruction so the process does not run as root inside the container, and prefer Podman's rootless mode so a container escape cannot trivially become host root. For multi-container applications, a <span class='keyterm'>compose</span> file (<code>docker-compose.yml</code> or <code>podman-compose</code>) declares the services, their networks, and their volumes in one place, and bringing the stack up or down becomes a single command. Cleaning up is its own discipline, since stopped containers, dangling images, and unused volumes accumulate; <code>podman system prune</code> reclaims the lot, and naming volumes deliberately keeps the ones holding real data from being swept away.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Persistent data needs a volume (<code>-v host:container</code>); without one, everything written lives in the throwaway overlay layer and is lost when the container is removed. Port mapping (<code>-p host:container</code>) is required for bridge networking but not for host networking, where ports are shared directly.</div>"}
);
